, and spanning in date from the eighth through the fourteenth centuries. Exploring reclusion and materiality, the collection addresses a series of overlapping themes, including the importance of touch, the limits of religious authority, and the role of the senses. Objects, metaphorical and real, embodied and spiritual, populate the pages. These categories are permeable, with flexible and porous boundaries, demonstrating the conflation of ideas, concepts, and manifestations in medieval materiality. In fact, the permeability of these categories demonstrates how materiality can reshape our approach to medieval texts. It leaves room for directions for future study, including the application of material analysis to previously unstudied objects, spaces, and literary artifacts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aChristian literature, English (Middle)xHistory and criticism. 0aMaterial culture in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMiddle English literature.  aanchorites.  aancrenne wisse.  aembodiment.  amedieval materiality.  amedieval relics.  areclusion.1 aBledsoe, Jenny C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBledsoe, Jenny C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Jennifer N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEasterling, Joshua S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodfrey, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckay, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauer, Michelle M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauer, Michelle M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSawicka-Sykes, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/